english:
  title: Inscribed on the Guest Pavilion of Changtang
  author: Kim Suon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Once Changtang was merely a small county,
    Now elevated to the rank of provincial seat.
    Relocated anew among the mountain valleys,
    Yet the work of building remains barely begun.
    The government hall and eastern office lean askew—
    Who is left to care for their decay?
    Only the scholar's words remain,
    Radiant with the brilliance of their prose.

    I have sat here long this day,
    Watching clerks bow and pay their respects.
    Lingjang and Linjin, two settlements of old,
    Once served as administrative stations too.
    Now, deemed too small to stand alone,
    They are merged into Changtang's embrace.
    The ancient grounds lie desolate,
    Where grass and dew pool deep in former pools.
    Only the temple of the city god stands proud,
    Watching over ancient trees between the old stronghold walls.

    Some travelers rest but a breath or two,
    Others must cross the great river to press on.
    The people hurry back and forth in hardship,
    Forgetting sleep and meals from dawn to dusk.
    Such is the way of rise and fall—
    Where gain and loss are hard to reckon.
    When the east grows full, the west empties.
    When the field dries for plowing, rain comes at harvest.

    What crime brought that county's end?
    What virtue grants this one its growth?
    The court has issued its final command—
    In truth, to bring prosperity to the people.
    So I tell the village elders this:
    Neither rejoice nor despair.
    What words has a passing traveler to offer?
    I ask only: which way leads forward?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Lingjang (臨江) and Linjin (臨津) were administrative divisions that were absorbed into Changtang following a territorial reorganization.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'city god temple' (城隍堂) refers to a traditional Korean shrine dedicated to the protective deity of a locality.
  - key: ''
    value: The poem reflects on the transience of administrative borders and human prosperity, a common theme in Korean literati poetry of the period.
